[2]
Date: 2 Feb 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Reuters AlertNet [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/L02120157.htm>

Seychelles said on Thursday it had mobilized its army to control an
incurable crippling mosquito-borne disease that has affected
thousands of people on the idyllic Indian ocean archipelago.
Over the last 4 weeks, 2000 of the island's 80 000 people have been
afflicted with chikungunya fever, named after a Swahili word meaning
"which bends up" and referring to the stooped posture of those afflicted.
The disease, first recognized in epidemic form in East Africa in
1952, is marked by high fever and severe rashes, and while health
officials say most people eventually recover, it is extremely painful
and there is no known cure or vaccine.
It also leaves immune systems weak, providing opportunities for other
diseases to set in.
"Cases of the disease have been doubling every week, with 200 having
been reported during the 1st week of January, 300 during the 2nd, and
513 in the 3rd week," Dr Jude Gedeon, director for community health,
told Reuters. "We are still counting but the number is quickly
approaching 1000 for this week."
Gedeon blamed the rise in the number of cases on heavier than normal
rainfall over the last 3 months and said a task force has been set up
to help control the spread of the epidemic which can transfer from
person to person [via the insect vector - CopyEd.PG].
The Seychelles military has been called in to provide personnel and
transport and help authorities clear areas prone to mosquito-breeding
such as stagnant pools of water and to spray areas where cases of the
viral infection have been found.
Gedeon said that as people continue to be affected, work output
suffers as thousands people go on sick leave.
The epidemic has affected other islands in the Indian Ocean region,
which relies heavily on tourism for foreign revenue.
France's Reunion island has reported 50 000 cases so far and last
week earmarked $720 000 to fight the outbreak, drafting 400 extra
troops to help fight the mosquitoes that have spread the disease
across the volcanic island for nearly a year.
Neighboring Mauritius has also reported 15 cases since the beginning
of January 2006 and authorities are screening people at the airport
and port, spraying places near hotels and guest houses and warning
the public to take precautions.
Authorities say people should remove stagnant water, use mosquito
repellents and bed nets, and spray bedrooms at night.
[Byline: George Thande]
