[3]
Date: Wed, 25 Jan 2006 10:49:46 -0500 (EST)
From: Mohammad Issack <missack@intnet.mu>
Source: Seychelles Nation online, 25 Jan 2006 [edited]
<http://www.nation.sc/>

The Department of Health will now take legal action against people
who do not take measures to control mosquito breeding within the
premises in which they live. Similar action will be taken against
proprietors of buildings which house a number of families or
businesses. This measure comes in the wake of confirmation that
samples taken overseas for analysis have proved positive for
Chikungunya, and the news that the disease has affected 847 people in
Seychelles so far.
The disease, which is believed to have been brought in by a foreigner
who stayed at Anse aux Pins where victims among Seychellois were
first reported, has now spread throughout Mahe, and also reached
Praslin and La Digue where cases are being reported.
Medical entomologist Simon Julienne announced the intention of the
department to take legal action Tuesday 24 Jan 2005 during a press
conference that was also addressed by the director general for
community health, Dr Jude Gedeon, and the director for environmental
health, Danny Poiret. Dr Gedeon said that the debilitating though
non-fatal viral disease is still in epidemic proportions in Reunion,
where over 7000 cases have been reported [more than 10 000 cumulative
cases to date, see also ProMED archive number <20060121.0202>], as
well as in other Indian Ocean island nations, including Mauritius,
Comoros and Madagascar. Mr Julienne said culprits will be those whose
septic tanks are leaking, residents who allow tall grass or bushes
within their compounds and those who [in]discriminately dispose of
waste, particularly that which has receptacles which can hold water.
The doctor and health officers said that the eastern part of Mahe is
most affected, and that more women than men have fallen victim to
Chikungunya. They attributed the gender bias to the possibility that
women spend more time indoors than men. They said the villain _Culex_
mosquito bites indoors and usually in the evening.
They advised people to use insect repellents and to spray their
houses with knockdown insecticides in the evening, allowing the
aerosols at least 10 minutes to act on the vectors. "There may be no
ready-made nets but the materials to make some are available locally
and people may consider making and using them," Mr Julienne said.
Dr Gedeon reassured the public that infection results in long-lasting
immunity, but expressed regret that affected people suffer headaches
and joint pains which makes it hard for them to work, which in the
end is affecting the country total work output.
He said that the disease, being viral, has no cure but is
self-limiting, and that doctors are currently giving medicine to
relieve the pain and effects of the joint inflammation.
The team said that widespread spraying would have negative effects on
the environment and might cause reactions in people who are sensitive
to pesticides, while the mosquitoes could develop resistance or
immunity to chemicals that would be used.
--
Dr. Mohammad Iqbal Issack
Pathologist (Microbiology)
Central Health Laboratory
Mauritius
<missack@intnet.mu>
[Thanks to Dr. Mohammad Igbal Issack for providing the report on
chikungunya outbreak in Seychelles from a local source. Chikungunya
is caused by chikungunya virus, pertaining to genus _Alphavirus_,
family _Togaviridae_; with spherical, enveloped virion 60 nm in
diameter, single-stranded, positive-sense RNA genome. Chikungunya is
transmitted by virus-infected mosquitoes.
Chikungunya is currently rampant in the neighboring island countries,
such as Reunion Island (see also prior ProMED postings below).
Readers may be interested in knowing the geographic location and
history of Seychelles, an independent republic within the British
Commonwealth of Nations since 1976. (see also
<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Image:Se-map.gif>
<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seychelles>). - Mod.RY]
